HEADWORD: Debtor
<hw>Debt"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>dettur</ets>, <ets>dettour</ets>, OF. <ets>detor</ets>,
<ets>detur</ets>, <ets>detour</ets>, F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧biteur</ets>, fr.
L. <ets>debitor</ets>, fr. <ets>debere</ets> to owe. See
<er>Debt</er>.]</ety> <def>One who owes a debt; one who is indebted; --
correlative to <xex>creditor</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I 'll] bring your latter hazard back again,⟦br⟧
And thankfully rest <qex>debtor</qex> for the first.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In Athens an insolvent <qex>debtor</qex> became slave to his
creditor.</q> <rj><qau>Mitford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Debtors</qex> for our lives to you.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Debulliate</ent>⟦br⟧
